<p>A typical residential solar installation in Idaho can produce between 1,200 to 1,400 kilowatt-hours per kilowatt of installed capacity annually, depending on location, system orientation, and shading factors. South-facing roofs with minimal shading perform optimally, though east and west-facing installations can still achieve 80-90% of optimal production. Idaho's northern latitude means solar panels perform exceptionally well during the long summer days, often producing peak power for 6-8 hours daily during June and July. Even during winter months, the state's clear skies and reflective snow cover help maintain reasonable solar production levels, typically 40-60% of summer output.</p>

