<h2>Idaho Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Idaho offers several attractive incentives for solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems, making these improvements more affordable for homeowners. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then reduces to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, providing substantial savings for Idaho homeowners investing in solar energy.</p>

<p>Idaho provides a valuable property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added home value from solar installation is exempt from property taxes. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial solar installations and remains in effect for the life of the system. Additionally, Idaho does not charge state sales tax on solar equipment purchases, reducing the upfront cost of solar installations by an additional 6%.</p>

<p>Idaho Power offers several programs supporting energy efficiency and renewable energy adoption. Their Energy Efficiency Program provides rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, including up to \$700 for qualifying heat pumps and \$400 for high-efficiency air conditioners. The utility also offers custom incentives for comprehensive home energy upgrades that include multiple efficiency measures. Idaho Power's Schedule 84 net metering program allows solar customers to receive full retail credit for excess generation, maximizing the financial benefits of solar installations.</p>

<p>The state's focus on renewable energy development includes workforce training programs and streamlined permitting processes that help reduce installation costs and timeframes. Many Idaho municipalities have adopted expedited permitting for solar installations, with some offering same-day permit approvals for standard residential systems. Intermountain Gas also provides rebates for high-efficiency natural gas heating equipment, offering additional savings for customers choosing efficient gas furnaces or combination heating systems.</p>

